Problem: Duplicate Telegram transaction entries

What happened:
When a user sent a Telegram command like "expense coffee 6.50 food", the bot created a new MongoDB transaction every time it processed that message. If Telegram delivered the same update twice, Render restarted during processing, or two bot instances briefly ran with the same BOT_TOKEN, the same command could create duplicate entries.

Root cause:
The Transaction document did not store the Telegram message identity. The bot had no way to know whether a specific Telegram chat/message pair had already been processed.

Solution:
Each Telegram-created transaction now stores:
- source: "telegram"
- telegramChatId
- telegramUserId
- telegramMessageId

Before creating a transaction, the bot checks for an existing Transaction with the same telegramChatId and telegramMessageId. If one exists, the bot skips creation and replies that the message was already saved.

Extra database protection:
The Transaction schema now has a unique partial index on:
- telegramChatId
- telegramMessageId

That prevents duplicate Telegram messages from creating duplicate records even if two bot processes try to save the same update at nearly the same time.

Operational note:
Only one polling bot instance should run with a BOT_TOKEN. In production, keep the Render bot running and stop any local server using the same token.

Problem: Old Telegram update created an unexpected transaction

What happened:
After the bot started or reconnected, Telegram could deliver an older pending update that was sent before the current bot process started. If that old update was an expense or income command, the bot could save it even though the user was expecting only their new query to run.

Root cause:
Telegram polling works like a mailbox. Messages that were not consumed while the bot was offline or restarting can still be waiting. The bot did not check whether a message was older than the current process startup time.

Solution:
The bot now records a startup timestamp:
- botStartedAt

Before handling any Telegram message, it checks:
- if msg.date is older than botStartedAt, ignore it

This prevents old queued Telegram commands from creating surprise transactions after a Render restart or local bot restart.

Problem: Telegram recent and summary commands did not work as slash commands

What happened:
Users expected Telegram commands like "/summary" and "/recent" to work from the Telegram command menu, but the bot only recognized plain text messages like "summary" and "recent".

Root cause:
The bot command matching only accepted the exact words:
- summary
- recent

Telegram slash commands include a leading slash, and in some contexts Telegram can include the bot username too, such as:
- /summary
- /summary@TrackerBot
- /recent
- /recent@TrackerBot

Solution:
The bot now accepts both plain text and Telegram slash command versions:
- summary
- /summary
- /summary@BotName
- recent
- /recent
- /recent@BotName

The help text now also shows "/summary" and "/recent" so users know these are real Telegram commands.
